  "text": "We begin with a more detailed analysis of the multi-object miss-distances mentioned in the introduction. From a mathematical point of view, the fundamental requirement to allow for consistent distance measuring is that our miss-distances are metrics on the space of finite sets of objects [CITATION_1] . For completeness, we recall the definition of a metric. Let be an arbitrary nonempty set. A function is called a metric if it satisfies the following three axioms: 1) (identity): if and only if ; 2) (symmetry): for all ; 3) (triangle inequality) : for all . In the context of multi-object miss-distances, we fix a closed and bounded observation window , and choose to be the set of finite subsets of . In what follows, denotes always the metric used on (typically the Euclidean metric, ) while for the various metrics considered on appropriate indexes are attached ( , or ).",
